function replaceElementWithForm(elementId, url, successCallback) {
  // Get the element to be replaced
  var element = document.getElementById(elementId);

  // Create a form element
  var form = document.createElement('form');
  form.method = 'post';
  form.action = url;

  // Create input fields for each attribute of the element
  for (var i = 0; i < element.attributes.length; i++) {
    var attr = element.attributes[i];
    var input = document.createElement('input');
    input.type = 'text';
    input.name = attr.name;
    input.value = attr.value;
    form.appendChild(input);
  }

  // Create a submit button
  var submitButton = document.createElement('input');
  submitButton.type = 'submit';
  form.appendChild(submitButton);

  // Replace the original element with the form
  element.parentNode.replaceChild(form, element);

  // Handle form submission asynchronously
  form.addEventListener('submit', function(event) {
    event.preventDefault();
    var formData = new FormData(form);
    fetch(url, {
      method: 'POST',
      body: formData
    })
    .then(response => response.json())
    .then(data => successCallback(data))
    .catch(error => console.error('Error:', error));
  });
}
```

This function first retrieves the element to be replaced using its ID. It then creates a form element with the specified method and action URL. For each attribute of the original element, it adds an input field to the form. A submit button is also added to the form. After replacing the original element with the form, it adds an event listener to the form for the submit event. When the form is submitted, it prevents the default form submission behavior, creates a FormData object from the form, sends a POST request to the specified URL using the Fetch API, and handles the response asynchronously by calling the success callback function with the data returned from the server. If an error occurs during the fetch operation, it is logged to the console. ```

